# Fixing the R6 Method Override Error

The error occurs because you're creating a dynamic method `foo` in the parent class during initialization, but trying to override it with a static method in the child class, which creates a conflict.

## Solution 1: Define Both Methods Statically (Recommended)

The simplest approach is to define `foo` as a static method in the parent class:

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      print('foo')
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      super$foo()
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # This will now work
```

## Solution 2: Define Both Methods Dynamically

If you really need to create methods dynamically, then do it consistently in both classes:

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      self[["foo"]] <- function() {
        print('foo')
      }
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      super$initialize()
      parent_foo <- self$foo
      self[["foo"]] <- function() {
        parent_foo()
      }
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # This will now work
```

The issue stems from mixing static class definitions with dynamic method creation, which conflicts with how R6 manages method bindings.

